INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '92bd9e4e-2d51-4f4b-84a6-195daeab4fe4',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Django Project Structure — App-per-Feature vs Traditional MTV Layering$escape$,
  $escape$Django's default layout encourages a flat `models.py / views.py / urls.py` per app, which works fine at small scale but degrades fast. Once an app crosses ~5 models, you end up with 800-line files and circular imports.

The vertical slice pattern reorganizes each Django app into a self-contained feature folder:

```
users/
  models.py
  services.py      # business logic, no HTTP
  selectors.py     # read queries (Django ORM)
  views.py         # thin — calls services/selectors only
  urls.py
  serializers.py
  tests/
```

This mirrors HackSoft's Django Styleguide and maps cleanly onto Django's app registry — each folder is still a proper `INSTALLED_APP`. The key rule: **views never touch ORM directly**. They call `selectors.get_user_by_id()` or `services.create_user()`, keeping Django's ORM power in a testable layer. Split `models.py` into `models/user.py` + `models/__init__.py` once it exceeds ~3 models. Use `django.urls.include()` to compose app-level `urls.py` into the root router cleanly.$escape$,
  $escape$# users/selectors.py
from django.db.models import QuerySet
from .models import User

def get_active_users() -> QuerySet[User]:
    return User.objects.filter(is_active=True).select_related("profile")

# users/services.py
from .models import User

def deactivate_user(*, user_id: int) -> User:
    user = User.objects.get(pk=user_id)
    user.is_active = False
    user.save(update_fields=["is_active"])
    return user

# users/views.py
from django.http import JsonResponse
from . import selectors

def active_users_view(request):
    qs = selectors.get_active_users()
    return JsonResponse({"count": qs.count()})$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
